observations.recommendation:
We recommended the LCE require:

Acting MT to furnish the MA a duly certified list showing the names of the taxpayers or the RPTAR which was based on the assessment rolls received from the Municipal Assessor;

MA to establish at the beginning of each year the RPT/SET Receivable and Deferred RPT Income/ SET Income accounts based on the RPTAR;

MA to tally with the list of tax delinquents maintained by the Acting MT in order to fairly present the financial statement and avoid the understatements of the said receivable and the deferred income accounts.

We recommended that the LCE:

Require the Acting MT to submit the CRAAF not later than the fifth day of the ensuing month to ensure proper monitoring of all accountable forms;

Require the MA and Municipal Budget Officer to prepare and submit the monthly Pre-Closing Trial Balance and SAAO not later that the 20th day after the end of the month for immediate preparation of year-end FS, and for easy determination of the status and balances of the appropriations;

Require the MA to prepare and submit the monthly BRS in accordance with COA Circular No. 96-011 to ensure the immediate reconciliation of the books and the depository bank.

We recommend that the LCE:

instruct the MT to impose internal rules in the movement or flow of transactions, like the claiming of checks, in order to expedite submission of reports and documents to the Municipal Accountant for submission of the latter to the Auditor;

instruct the MA to retrieve all documents from the BAC Secretariat which remained unsubmitted. Disbursement vouchers that had been paid and transmitted to the Municipal Accountant should remain in his possession until its submission to the Auditor;

remind the MA to strictly observe the timely and complete submission of accounts, in order to facilitate immediate review, evaluation and examination of consummated transactions, thus financial/ operational deficiencies, if any, could be communicated to Management for its immediate and appropriate action.

We recommended that the LCE direct the:

End-users or implementing units to prepare their respective PPMPs, containing all PPAs under their units, for consolidation into an APP by the BAC Secretariat;

BAC Chairman and the Secretariat to submit the final APP, including amendments, revisions and supplemental, to the GPPB on or before the end of January of the budget year;

ME to prepare the necessary Technical Specifications of infrastructure projects;

BAC Chairman to not assign the OIC-ME, being an end-user for infrastructure projects and an automatic member of the BAC, as member of the TWG;

BAC Chairman to cover all the necessary activities in the conduct of Pre-Procurement Conference in order to ensure readiness of the procurement at hand;

BAC Chairman to invite representative from a specific relevant chamber-member of the Philippine Chamber of Commerce and Industry as observer in the procurement of goods and services;

BAC Secretariat to post the NOA and NTP in the PhilGEPS website within the prescribed period of 3 and 15 calendar days, respectively, in order to ensure procurement transparency;

BAC Secretariat to see to it that all documents submitted by the contractors, especially the Performance Security, are duly dated to ensure that said security was posted prior to the signing of the contract;

MA to deduct from the payment to the concerned supplier or require either retention money, in the procured goods or services, in an amount equivalent to at least one percent  but not to exceed five percent  of every progress payment, or a special bank guarantee equivalent to at least one percent  but not to exceed five percent of the total contract, to ensure that there is a warranty security that may compel suppliers/ manufacturers to undertake the necessary repairs on manufacturing defect within a period of one year from the date of purchase.;

MA to require, prior to the release of retention money of infrastructure projects, a letter request for substitution of the retention money from the contractor and a warranty security equivalent thereto; and

BAC, BAC Secretariat and TWG Members of the Municipality, at all times, be guided with the 2016 Revised IRR of RA 9184 in the procurement of goods and services, and infrastructure projects to avoid the sanction provided therein. Likewise, we encourage them to attend seminars related to the procurement processes to keep them abreast on the latest updates and issues.

We recommended the LCE:

instruct the LDRRMO to prepare the CY 2024 LDRRMFIP and incorporate in the unexpended balance of LDRRMF for CYs 2019 to CY 2023 with an aggregate balance of ₱22,584,451.48 to support the release and use of the LDRRMF in order ensure the most possible available funds for disaster risk reduction and the validity of disbursements made;

instruct the MA to revert back to the unappropriated surplus of the GF and shall be made available for other social services after subsequent enactment by the local sanggunian the unexpended balance of STF for CYs 2017 to CY 2018 amounting to ₱1,377,302.35;

require the LDRRMO and MA to follow the breakdown of the STF and Continuing Appropriations balances in order to correctly determine the charges thereto; and

require and LDRRMO and MA determine the priority programs and project initially recognized as Capital Outlay and make continuing its possible implementation, otherwise request for its reprogramming.

The Audit Team recommended that the LCE instruct the:
Acting MT to immediately deposit the amount of ₱2,139,480.49;
Acting MT to see to it that collections are deposited daily and intact with the authorized depository bank maintained by the Municipality in line with PD No. 1445 to avoid the risk of possible misappropriation/ misuse and/or loss of government funds;
Acting MT to closely monitor the collections and deposits, keep the cashbooks updated and conduct monthly reconciliation with the ledger of the Municipal Accountant, thus both records are reconciled for any discrepancies.

The Audit Team recommended that the LCE instruct the MA to:
Determine the unclaimed retention money for its possible payment and coordinate with the ME for the issuance of Certificate of Final Acceptance for these projects which will serve as their basis in the preparation of the Disbursement Voucher even without request for payment from the contractors/supplier;
Make a compilation of any record/ documentation and prepare the corresponding assessment/evaluation report as regards the long outstanding liabilities to support the possible reversion to unappropriated surplus in order not to overstate the liability accounts.  Likewise, attach the Subsidiary ledgers and all available records to support the amount of the Journal Entry Voucher (JEV) that has to be prepared in case of reversion to the unappropriated surplus. If there may be claims in the future, the JEV would serve as the basis in requesting for a supplemental budget for the settlement of the payable;
Reclassify ₱22,624,782.36 Government Equity under “Equity” instead of payables to reflect the true nature of the account.
Determine the cause/s of the negative balances after which prepare the correct and for appropriate adjusting entries.
Avoid the setting up or recognizing payables at year-end without complete and valid documents supporting the claims to prevent bloating the payable account.

In view of the forgoing, the Audit Team recommended the Local Chief Executive to direct the Municipal Accountant to:
See to it that transactions are properly classified in accordance with the Revised Chart of Accounts for LGUs;
Make the following adjusting or correcting entries to fairly present the FS:

The Audit Team recommended that the LCE direct the:
End-users or implementing units to prepare their respective PPMPs, containing all PPAs under their units, for consolidation into an APP by the BAC Secretariat;
BAC Chairman and the Secretariat to submit the final APP, including amendments, revisions and supplemental, to the GPPB on or before the end of January of the budget year;
BAC Chairman to cover all the necessary activities in the conduct of Pre-Procurement Conference in order to ensure readiness of the procurement at hand and ensure completeness of bidding documents;
BAC Chairman to make sure that the Approved Technical Specifications for the procurement of infrastructure projects are prepared;
BAC to ensure that Post-Qualification Reports are prepared solely by the BAC or its Technical Working Group (TWG);
BAC Secretariat to limit its role to administrative and logistical support functions, as outlined in Section 14.1 of the IRR.
Direct the Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) to strictly adhere to the procurement procedures under Section 53.14 of the 2016 Revised IRR of RA 9184 for the acquisition of petroleum fuel, oil, and lubricants.
BAC, BAC Secretariat and TWG Members of the Municipality, at all times, be guided with the IIRR of RA No. 12009 or the New Government Procurement Act in the procurement of goods and services, and infrastructure projects to avoid the sanction provided therein. Likewise, we encourage them to attend seminars related to the procurement processes to keep them abreast of the latest updates and issuance.

Ther Audit Team recommended that the LCE:
Require the Acting MT to send demand letters for the immediate liquidation of the cash advances and ensure that the same is received by the concerned persons and seek legal remedies so that the unliquidated cash advances of those accountable persons who were no longer in service will be settled the soonest possible time;
Remind the MA and the Acting MT to observe compliance with the provisions of COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 10, 1997 and Section 89 of PD No. 1445 for the liquidation of cash advances within the prescribed period and that no additional cash advance shall be granted to any official or employee unless the previous cash advance given to him is first settled or a proper accounting thereof is made to avoid misappropriation and/or loss of government funds;
Require the Acting MT to submit all Liquidation Reports for payroll related cash advances, to the MA within the required liquidation period to ensure timely and accurate recording and immediate submission to the Office of the Auditor;

The Audit Team recommended that the LCE:
Instruct the Acting MT to ensure the timely preparation and turnover of collection and disbursement reports, including all supporting documents, to the MA for prompt submission to the Auditor, and to establish internal controls to monitor compliance with submission deadlines;
Direct the Acting MT to submit the pending liquidation reports for payroll and the reports of collections and deposits covering the period from January to December 2024;
Remind the MA to strictly observe the timely and complete submission of accounts to facilitate immediate review, evaluation, and examination of consummated transactions, enabling prompt communication of any financial or operational deficiencies to Management for appropriate action;
Require the MA to immediately submit the 141 unsubmitted disbursement vouchers as shown in Annex B which was attached in AOM No. 2025-008 dated May 22, 2025 which was received by Management.

The Audit Team recommended that the LCE:
Require the Acting MT to submit the CRAAF not later than the fifth day of the ensuing month to ensure proper monitoring of all accountable forms;
Require the MA and Municipal Budget Officer to prepare and submit the monthly Pre-Closing Trial Balance and SAAO not later that the 20th day after the end of the month for immediate preparation of year-end FS, and for easy determination of the status and balances of the appropriations;
Require the MA to prepare and submit the monthly BRS in accordance with COA Circular No. 96-011 to ensure the immediate reconciliation of the books and the depository bank.

The Audit Team recommended that the LCE:
Direct the Acting MT and the MA to identify TF accounts that are not specifically required by source agencies to be held separately, and to facilitate their closure and consolidation;
Request from the SB to coordinate with the depositary bank regarding the Ordinance previously enacted which said bank deemed not acceptable in order to immediately facilitate the opening of the TF account;
Seek authority from the SB to close the dormant or inactive accounts and transfer the balances to the new TF account;
Instruct the Acting MT to initiate the disposal process for the 1,507 obsolete checks and formally request relief from accountability over the unused accountable forms.

The Audit Team recommended that the LCE direct the:
Acting MT and MA to coordinate with the Provincial Treasurer to reconcile their records to determine the correct amount of the shares from basis RPT and SET due to the Provincial Government;
Acting MT to facilitate the immediate remittance of the Provincial shares from basic RPT and SET;
Acting MT to immediately release the shares of the barangays from the basic RPT collections amounting to ₱1,315,651.64 and the barangay clearance fees amounting to ₱1,483,134.51, or a total of ₱2,798,786.15;
Both the Acting MT and MA to establish a systematic schedule and monitoring mechanism to ensure timely remittance of provincial shares from basic RPT and SET and the release of barangay share within five days after the end of the quarter, in order not to deprived the immediate use of said funds for the implementation of PPAs;
Further, we recommended that the LCE consider the process of Auto Debit Arrangement (ADA) with the maintained depositary bank to facilitate the direct and timely remittance of barangay shares to their respective bank accounts, thereby reducing administrative delays and clerical workload.

The Audit Team recommended that the LCE to:
Direct the Acting MT and MA to conduct a comprehensive reconciliation of all unremitted withheld taxes, including those long outstanding from CY 2019 to 2024, investigate and correct negative and stagnant balances, making necessary adjustment if necessary and prepare an updated schedule reflecting the accurate balance;
Instruct the Acting MT to immediately remit the total unremitted balance of withheld taxes to the BIR after determining the correct balance of unremitted taxes, thereby ensuring accurate remittance and avoiding further penalties, surcharges, and interest;
Ensure the Acting MT submits all disbursement vouchers related to tax remittances without delay to the MA for timely recording in the books; and
Require the Acting MT and MA to establish and maintain a regular monthly reconciliation process of withheld taxes to prevent recurrence of delays, discrepancies, and non-compliance with applicable BIR regulations.

The Audit Team recommended that the LCE direct the MA and Acting MT to:
Immediately coordinate with the GSIS for a full reconciliation of the Municipality’s unpaid premium contributions and loan amortizations, including verification of accounts with negative balances and noted discrepancies;
Prioritize the remittance of the ₱1,049,613.68 outstanding GSIS obligations, ensuring compliance with Section 14.1 of the IRR of RA No. 8291, which mandates that remittance of GSIS contributions take precedence over all other financial obligations except salaries and wages in order to avoid the incurrence of penalties and administrative sanctions under Sections 5 and 7 of RA No. 8291 and will safeguard the welfare and entitlements of the Municipality’s officers and employees;
Institute procedures to strictly remit all GSIS contributions and deductions within the prescribed ten (10) days of the succeeding month, supported by complete documentation; and
Implement internal control measures—such as a monthly GSIS reconciliation schedule, tracking of withheld deductions, and joint certification of remittances by the MA and Acting MT—to prevent future delays and ensure continued eligibility of municipal employees to GSIS benefits and loans.

The Audit Team recommended that the LCE:
require the MA and other persons responsible to immediately cause the settlement of audit suspensions in order to avoid maturing into audit disallowances;
require the MA to inform persons liable to immediately cause the settlement of disallowances especially those with issued NFD or inform them to file an appeal, if still within six (6) months from receipt of the ND so as not to deprive them for any possibility for the lifting of ND if warranted by the merits presented;
direct the Acting MT, in compliance with the directives of the issued COE, to withhold the payment of the salaries or any amount due to the persons liable, if still in service, for the settlement of their liabilities;
direct the Municipal Administrator and Acting MT to cause the collection or settlement of the disallowances directly from the persons liable who are no longer in the service by sending Demand Letters or employ legal remedies if necessary, so as not to deprive the Municipal Government for the funds which could be used to fund other priority projects for the benefit of the constituents.

We recommended that the LCE:

request from the Office of the Sanggunian for the creation of a Trust Fund depository account, if opted not to use one of the dormant TF accounts, in which all funds received for a specific purpose will be deposited and maintained;

request from the Office of the Sanggunian for the authority to close the dormant or in-active accounts and cause the transfer of any existing balance to the new TF account to be maintained;

require the Acting Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant to determine the existing TF accounts which are not required by the source national agency that separate bank accounts should be maintained in order to cause its closure and balances be transferred to the new TF account to be maintained; and

require the Acting Municipal Treasurer to request for the disposal of the obsolete checks to remove accountability over said accountable forms.

We recommended the LCE:

require the M to issue only system generated and duly dated OR, unless in times of power interruption which must be duly supported with proof, in order not expose the funds from possible risk of misappropriation and in order to strengthen the intern control in the issuance of receipts;

instruct the BAC Secretariat to release bidding documents only to prospective bidders upon presentation of a computer generated OR and if the bidding documents were downloaded in the PhilGEPs portal, to receive their bids only upon presentation of a computer generation OR;

require the Municipal Accountant, the internal auditor, to see to it that internal control systems installed are strictly followed.

We recommended that the municipality, through its Inventory and Appraisal Committee, ensure management and accounting of its properties by observing the procedures provided by existing rules and regulations in the custody and management of properties specifically:

Keeping of Property Cards per category of Property, Plant and Equipment by the General Services Officer, Supply Officer or the Local Treasurer, as the case maybe;
Maintaining Property, Plant and Equipment Ledger Cards for each category of assets and Real Property Ledger Cards for land by the Municipal Accountant;
Conducting annual physical inventory of all supplies or property of the local government unit as of December 31 of each year and submission of the report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE) to the auditor concerned not later than January 31 of each year.
Reconciling the balance of the Property, Plant and Equipment with property card, ledger cards and RPCPPE.

